think through our very relationship with technology and our possible ecological futures. Fisch provides an unblinking glimpse into what it might be like to inhabit a future in which more and more of our infrastructure-and the planet itself-will have to operate beyond capacity to accommodate our ever-growing population.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aRailroadszJapanzTokyoxCommuting traffic. 0aUrban transportationxSocial aspectszJapanzTokyo. 4aCollective. 4aCommuter train network. 4aFukushima. 4aGilbert Simondon. 4aInfrastructure. 4aJapan. 4aMachine. 4aMedia. 4aScience and Technology Studies. 4aTechnology. 4aTokyo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019z978311063851608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226558691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226558691.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-063851-6  DG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019c2016d2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles